### Factory Pattern

- Defines an interface for creating an object
- Subclasses alter the type of object created
- Useful when object creation involves complex logic or depends on conditions

**Example (Java):**
```java
public interface Product {}
public class ConcreteProductA implements Product {}
public class ConcreteProductB implements Product {}
public class Factory {
  public Product createProduct(String type) {
    if (type.equals("A")) return new ConcreteProductA();
    else return new ConcreteProductB();
  }
}
```

### Singleton Pattern

- Ensures a class has only one instance
- Provides a global point of access
- Useful for managing resources (e.g., database connections, configuration)

**Example (Java):**
```java
public class Singleton {
  private static Singleton instance;
  private Singleton() {}
  public static Singleton getInstance() {
    if (instance == null) {
      instance = new Singleton();
    }
    return instance;
  }
}
```
